78. Subsets

Given an integer array nums of unique elements, return all possible subsets (the power set).

The solution set must not contain duplicate subsets. Return the solution in any order.

Example 1:

Input: nums = [1,2,3]
Output: [[],[1],[2],[1,2],[3],[1,3],[2,3],[1,2,3]]
Example 2:

class
{
    public List<List<Integer>> subsets(int[] nums)
    {
        List<List<Integer>> res=new ArrayList<>();
        help(res,nums,new ArrayList<Integer>() ,0);
        return res;
    }
    public static void help(List<List<Integer>>res,int []nums,ArrayList<Integer> ar,int idx)
    {
        if( idx==nums.length)
        {
            res.add(new ArrayList<>(ar) );
            return;
        }
        //pick
        ar.add(nums[idx]);
        //not pick
        help(res,nums,ar,idx+1);
        ar.remove( ar.size()-1 );

        help(res,nums,ar,idx+1);
    }
}

✅ Brute Force Code
import java.util.*;

class Solution {
    public List<List<Integer>> subsets(int[] nums) {

        List<List<Integer>> res = new ArrayList<>();
        int n = nums.length;

        // total subsets = 2^n
        int total = 1 << n;

        for (int i = 0; i < total; i++) {

            List<Integer> temp = new ArrayList<>();

            for (int j = 0; j < n; j++) {

                // check if jth bit is set
                if ((i & (1 << j)) != 0) {
                    temp.add(nums[j]);
                }
            }

            res.add(temp);
        }

        return res;
    }
}

| Approach    | Method       | Time    | Space          |
| ----------- | ------------ | ------- | -------------- |
| Brute Force | Bit masking  | O(n·2ⁿ) | O(n·2ⁿ)        |
| Optimal     | Backtracking | O(n·2ⁿ) | O(n) recursion |

